snippet.textDisplay:
Sony, I don't believe that statement; "Our promise to the 100 million strong PlayStation Community is to offer the biggest and best content."
If Sony wants to provide their community the best gaming experience(best content), then they'd filter games that have Micro-transactions.
If, the scumbag devs/publishers micro-transaction game won't be able to be sold on Playstation, then the devs/publishers would reconsider adding Micro-transactions in a 60-80$ game.
Paying full price for a game just to not actually have the full game is always upsetting.
Even more so in places where you're unable to refund the game.
(And no, researching the game beforehand won't work- As Crash Team Racing added Micro-transactions AFTER Release)


PlayStation is one of the few who are able to make this change, and make games actually enjoyable and fun to play again.
Right now, nearly all AAA games have Micro-transactions. They design the game around this, making the game a Grindfest- Making problems in the game, and then selling the solution for it('Solution Selling')- It's all the same stuff. It honestly makes all games feel repetitive as in the players feel like they've already played the game before whilst being only five minutes in the game.
They feel like they've played it before because they have, essentially.
Grindfest, Solution Selling, Pay-2-Win, Day 1 DLC, cutting content from a full price game to add it later with another price tag(I'm looking at you, Pokemon Sword/Shield)-- It's all the same stuff, and because of this stuff games are feeling more of the same.


Here's my thoughts when playing a game that has Singleplayer, online, and Micro-transactions;
"I noticed they have Micro-transactions.... So I guess this game is going to be boring Grindfest that sells solutions to problems that they intentionally put into the game... woo.
So... I noticed Campaign getting progressively harder- It's going to do this until it's nearly impossible to beat without grinding for 72 hours non-stop, or paying 4.99$, right?.. Yep. Great. I can't even refund this. RIP 80$
... Oh? It has online, too? I suppose the player who pays the most money is going to always win, they have better gear than anyone else. The Better Payer is The Better Player, after all.

Notice how it's a mostly negative experience? That's where games are heading.
Some games even attempt to give their players- Kids and adults alike- gambling addictions- then using said addictions to take money from them. Doesn't sound too fun, does it?


I highly doubt they will even attempt my Idea, let alone consider it.
But if they did, then that'd be highly, Highly incredible.
